Benzofluorene-containing  angucyclines  are  a  growing  family  of  natural  products  with  diverse  biological  activities.1,2    Family  lomaiviticins,6,7  members  momofulvenones,8  and  fluostatins  (Fig.  1).9-14    The  well  known  lomaiviticins  are  isolated  from  Salinispora  strains,  a  genus  of  indigenous  marine  halophilic  bacteria,  and  display  potent  antitumor  activities.2,6,7  Lomaiviticins  are  unique  to  have  a  C-2  symmetric diazobenzo[b]fluorene dimeric structure, in which the  diazofluorene  moiety  is  demonstrated  to  be  a  key  functional  group  cytotoxicities  of  nanomolar-picomolar  concentrations  toward  a  panel  of  human  cancer  cell  lines  by  inducing  double-strand  breaks  in  DNA.15-17    Currently,  the  most  potent lomaiviticin A is undergoing preclinical evaluation for the  treatment of DNA double-strand break repair deficient tumors.16   Kinamycins  are  the  first  known  naturally  occurring  compounds  with  a  benzo[b]fluorene  skeleton,3  while  fluostatins  contain  a  distinct benzo[a]fluorene scaffold and are recently discovered by  traditional  isolation  method,9-12  metagenomic  approach,13  and  heterologous  expression  studies.14    The  unique  structures  and  remarkable  pharmaceutical  potential  of  benzofluorenes  have  attracted significant attentions for total synthesis and biosynthesis  ———   Corresponding author. Type your Abstract text here  Benzofluorene-containing angucyclines, such as lomaiviticins, kinamycins, and fluostatins, have  attracted  increasing  attentions  on  their  chemical  synthesis  and biosynthesis  due  to  their  unique  structures and potent biological activities.  Our continuous searching for novel natural products  the  discovery  of  nenestatin  A  (1),  a  from  deep-sea  derived  actinomycetes  benzo[b]fluorene  compound  possessing  a  carbon  scaffold  similar  the  monomeric  lomaiviticins,  from  the  deep  sea-derived  Micromonospora  echinospora  SCSIO  04089.    In  addition,  the  biosynthetic  gene  cluster  of  nenestatin  A  (nes)  was  identified  by  a  genome  sequencing approach and comparative bioinformatics analysis with the lomaiviticin biosynthetic  gene clusters. The nes-gene cluster was further verified by in vivo gene disruption experiments  to  afford a biosynthetic  intermediate  homo-dehydrorabelomycin  E  (2).   This study  adds  a  new  member  to  the  growing  family  of  benzofluorene  angucyclines  and  paves  the  way  for  further  biosynthetic investigations.

The  identification  and  characterization  of  biosynthetic  gene  clusters  for  kinamycins,20-23  lomaiviticins,24,25  and  fluostatins,13,14  reveal  a  common  origin  of  type  II  polyketide  synthase  (PKS)  pathway. Nenestatin A was elucidated to have a scaffold similar to  kinamycins,  momofulvenone,  and  the  monomeric  lomaiviticins.   It  also  contained  a  rare  sugar  4-O-methyl-angolosamine,31  different  from  N,N-dimethyl-L-pyrrolosamine  and  L-oleandrose  in  lomaiviticins.    In  addition,  the  biosynthetic  gene  cluster  for  nenestatin  A  (nes)  was  identified  from  M.  echinospora  SCSIO  04089  by  a  whole  genome  sequencing  approach  and  was  revealed  to  share  highly  similar  organization  with  the  lom  gene  clusters from S. tropica CNB-440, DPJ-0019, and DPJ-0016.24,25   Furthermore,  the  involvement  of  the  nes  gene  cluster  in  the  biosynthesis  of  nenestatin  A  was  validated  by  in  vivo  gene  disruptions,  and  the  identification  of  a  key  intermediate,  homo- dehydrorabelomycin E (2, Fig. 2),32 from the ∆nes27 mutant. Isolation and structure elucidation of nenestatin A

The Strain SCSIO 04089 was isolated from a sediment sample  at  the  depth  of  3025  m  from  the  northern  South  China  Sea  (E  119°31.949, N 18°2.441) and was identified as Micromonospora  echinospora  (Fig.  S1)  on  the  basis  of  its  16S  rDNA  gene  sequence  (GenBank  accession  no.  KY454836).    The  strain  M.  echinospora SCSIO 04089 was subjected to fermentation in eight  different  culturing  media  to  search  for  secondary  metabolites.   HPLC analysis of the butanone extracts of these cultures revealed  the presence of two major products in N4 and AM6-1 media (Fig.  2,  traces  A-H).    Subsequently,  a  20  L  fermentation  of  M.  echinospora SCSIO 04089 was performed in N4 media, resulting  fluostatin C (R = H) fluostatin D (R = COCHMe2) fluostatin F (R = Me) pyrazolofluostatin A (R1 = H, R2 = OH) pyrazolofluostatin B (R1 = OH, R2 = H) lomaiviticin C (R1 = H, R2 = H) lomaiviticin D (R1 = H, R2 = Me) lomaiviticin E (R1 = Me, R2 = Me) momofulvenone A (R = H) momofulvenone B (R = Ac) (M+ = different cations) in  the  isolation  and  characterization  of  a  new  compound  nenestatin A (1, Fig. 2).

The molecular formula of nenestatin A (1) was determined to  be  C28H31NO8  by  HRESIMS  (m/z  [M  +  H]+  510.2117,  calcd  510.2122). Inspection and comparison of 1D and 2D NMR data  of  1  (Table  S1,  Fig.  S2  and  S3)  and  lomaiviticin  C  showed  a  certain degree of similarity and revealed the presence of the same  trihydroxy-4H-cyclopenta[b]naphthalen-4-one  moiety  in  both  compounds.  The  assignments  of  7-OH  and  10-OH  were  supported by the HMBC correlations from 7-OH to C-6a/C-7/C-8  and from 10-OH to C-9/C-10/C-10a in 1 (Fig. 3).  The presence  of  a  cyclohexa-2,4-dienone  moiety  in  1  was  evident  from  the  following spectroscopic data: (i) the existence of a cis ∆1,2 double  bond deducing from the two olefinic protons at δH 7.52 (d, 10.0  Hz,  H-1)  and  δH  5.80  (d,  10.0  Hz,  H-2);  (ii)  the  HMBC  correlations  from  H-1  to  C-3/C-4a  and  from  H-2  to  C-4/C-11b.   These  two  moieties  were  fused  through  C-4a/C-11b,  which  was  indicated  by  the  HMBC  correlations  from  H-5  to  C-4a/C-11b,  from H-1 to C-4a, and from H-2 to C-11b (Fig. 3). Bacterial strains, plasmids, and Reagents  would  attach  a  4-O-methyl-angolosamine  to  the  aglycone  to  furnish  the  biosynthesis  of  nenestatin  A  (Fig.  5).    We  propose  that  the  biosynthesis  of  the  activated  4-O-methyl-angolosamine  followed  a  general  rule  of  NDP  sugar  pathway,40  which  was  initiated  by  the  formation  of  TDP-D-glucose  by  Nes60,  and  followed  by  the  4,6-dehydration  (Nes51)  to  afford  the  common  intermediate  TDP-4,6-dideoxy-D-gluocose  (Fig.  5).40    The  subsequent  2,3-dehydration  (Nes8)  and  3-amination  (Nes45  or  Nes50) led to TDP-2,3,6-trideoxy-3-amino-D-glucose, which was  converted  to  the  corresponding  L-configured  sugar  by  the  3,5- epimerase  (Nes46).  Finally,  TDP-4-O-methyl-L-angolosamine  was  produced  by  the  following  4-reduction  (Nes47),  N,N- dimethylation (Nes42) and 4-O-methylation (Nes41 or Nes44).

In summary, a new benzo[b]fluorene compound nenestatin A  (1)  was  isolated  from  the  deep  sea-derived  M.  echinospora  SCSIO  04089  and  the  nes-gene  cluster  of  nenestatin  A  biosynthesis was also identified and characterized by in vivo gene  disruptions.  The  isolation  of  homo-dehydrorabelomycin  E  (2)  from  the  ∆nes27  mutant  provides  confirmative  evidence  for  the  involvement  of  the  identified  gene  cluster  in  the biosynthesis  of  nenestatin  A.  Comparative  bioinformatic  analysis  reveals  the  high similarity of the nenestatin A and lomaiviticin gene clusters  and  leads  to  a  similar  biosynthetic  pathway,  including  a  conserved  set  of  enzymes  for  the  formation  of  a  diazo  group.   However,  distinct  tailoring  oxidative  modifications  make  the  biosynthesis  of  nenestatin  A  unique  from  lomaiviticins.  This  work  lays  the  foundation  for  future  studies  to  elaborate  the  genetic  and  biochemical  mechanisms  for  the  glycosylation  and  oxidative transformations in the biosynthesis of nenestatin A. Cultivation of bacterial strains

The  strain  M.  echinospora  SCSIO  04089  was  grown  and  maintained  on  ISP4-agar  containing  3%  sea  salt.  Seed  cultures  were  incubated  at  28  °C  and  200  rpm  for  3  days  and  were  transferred to 50 mL of each of the following media including N4  medium (soluble starch 15 g, fish peptone 8g, bacterial peptone 5  g/L, glycerol 7.5 g/L, CaCO3 2 g/L, KBr 0.2 g/L, sea salt 10 g/L,  pH7.0),14 AM6-1 medium (soluble starch 20 g/L, glycerol 10 g/L,  glycine 0.1 g/L, alanine 0.1 g/L, threonine 0.1 g/L, isoleucine 0.1  g/L, yeast extract 5 g/L, CaCO3 5 g/L, sea salts 30 g/L, pH 7.0),41  AM6-4  medium  (glycerol  10  g/L,  bacterial  peptone  5  g/L,  glycine  0.1  g/L,  alanine  0.1  g/L,  CaCO3  5  g/L,  pH  7.0),42  M- AM2ab  medium  (soluble  starch  5  g/L,  glucose  20  g/L,  yeast  extract  2  g/L,  bacterial  peptone  2  g/L,  soybean  meal  5  g/L,  MgSO4·7H2O 0.5 g/L, K2HPO4 0.5 g/L, NaCl 4 g/L, sea salts 30  g/L, CaCO3 2 g/L, pH 7.2-7.4),43 ISP4 medium [soluble starch 10  g/L,  (NH4)2SO4  2  g/L,  K2HPO4  1  g/L,  CaCO3

3 2 g/L, pH 7.2-7.4),43 ISP4 medium [soluble starch 10  g/L,  (NH4)2SO4  2  g/L,  K2HPO4  1  g/L,  CaCO3  1  g/L,  MgSO4·7H2O 1 g, trace elements 100 µL/L (FeSO4·H2O 0.1 g/ L ，MnCl2·4H2O 0.1 g/L，ZnSO4·7H2O 0.1 g/L), sea salts 30 g/L,  pH 7.2-7.4],41 M-RA medium [glucose 10 g/L, soluble starch 20  g/L, malt extract 10 g/L, corn flour 5 g/L, sea salts 30 g/L,  trace  elements  100  µL/L  (FeSO4·H2O  0.1  g/  L,  MnCl2·4H2O  0.1  g/L,  ZnSO4·7H2O  0.1  g/L),  pH  7.2-7.4],44  YMS  medium  (yeast  extract  4  g/L,  malt  extract  10  g/L,  soluble  starch  5  g/L,  CoCl2  0.05 g/L, sea salt 30 g/L, pH 7.2-7.4),45 ISP2 medium (glucose 4  g/L, malt extract 10 g/L, yeast extract 5 g/L, sea salt 30 g/L, pH  7.2-7.4).45  The  fermentation  was  carried  out  on  a  rotary  shaker  (200  rpm)  at  28  °C  for  7  days  and  the  metabolite  profiles  were  monitored  by  HPLC  analysis.  HPLC  analysis  was  carried  out  using  a  reversed  phase  column  Luna  C18,  5  µm,  150 ×  4.6  mm  (Phenomenex) with UV

by  HPLC  analysis.  HPLC  analysis  was  carried  out  using  a  reversed  phase  column  Luna  C18,  5  µm,  150 ×  4.6  mm  (Phenomenex) with UV detection at 480 nm on an Agilent series  1200  Station  under  the  following  program:  solvent  system  (solvent A, water supplemented with 0.05% formic acid and 10%  MeCN; solvent B, 90% MeCN with 0.05% formic acid); 5% B to  70% B (0-17 min), 100% B (18-19 min), 100% B to 5% B (19-25  min), 5% B (27-32 min); flow rate at 1 mL/min.

4.3. Identification of nenestatin A biosynthetic gene cluster  The  genome  sequencing  and  assembly  were  performed  at  Beijing  Institute  of  Genomics,  Chinese  Academy  of  Sciences.  The sequenced genome was of approximate 6.25 MB in size and  was distributed over 143 contigs. The biosynthetic  gene clusters  were  analyzed  by  antiSMASH  3.0.46    The  putative  nenestatin  A  gene  cluster  was  located  on  two  contigs  (15  and  61,  Fig.  S4).  Gaps  between  these  two  contigs  were  bridged  by  PCR.  The  genomic  library  of  M.  echinospora  SCSIO  04089  was  constructed  in  SuperCos1  by  using  the  Gigapack  III  Gold  Packaging  Extract  to  manufacturer's  instructions  (Stratagene).  The  positive  clones  covering  the  putative 1 gene cluster were screened by PCR with three primers  4089S1-F/R,  4089S3-F/R  and  4089S5-F/R  (Table  S5).  The  orfs  were  determined  by  using  the  FramePlot  4.0  beta  program  (http://nocardia.nih.go.jp/fp4/). Protein sequences were compared  with  BLAST  programs.  The  nucleotide  sequence  of  the  1  gene  cluster in SCSIO 04089 has been deposited to Genbank under the  accession number KY454837.  4.4. Construction of the mutant strains of M. echinospora SCSIO  04089  PCR  targeting  for  gene  disruption  in  M.  echinospora  SCSIO  04089 was performed according to previous methods.14  Briefly,  the  gene  cassette  comprising  aac(3)IV  and  oriT  was  amplified

from  plasmid  pIJ773  with  primers  nes53-tarF  and  nes53-tarR  (Table S5), and the purified PCR product was introduced into E.  coli  BW25113/pIJ790  containing  the  cosmid  pCSG4104  by  electroporation.  The positive clones where the targeted gene was  replaced  by  the  aac(3)IV  and  oriT  cassette  were  selected  with  apramycin  resistance  to  afford  the  cosmid  pCSG4129  carrying  the disrupted nes53 gene (Table S4).  The conjugation between E.  coli  ET12567/pUZ8002/pCSG4129  and  M.  echinospora  SCSIO  04089 was carried out in a similar way as previously described.14  The exconjugants were selected after 1~2 weeks and the double- crossover mutant strains were identified by diagnostic PCR with  primers  nes53testF  and  nes53testR  (Table  S5)  to  afford  the  ∆nes53 mutant (NES001). Two or three independent clones from  the  double-crossover  mutant  were  randomly  chosen  for  small  scale fermentation and subjected to HPLC analyses. The ∆nes27  mutant (NES002) was constructed in a similar way (Fig. S5).  4.5. Isolation of compounds

A  single  colony  of  SCSIO  04089  on  ISP4  medium  was  inoculated into a 250 mL Erlenmeyer flask containing 80 mL of  the  N4  medium.  After  incubating  on  a  rotary  shaker  (200  rpm)  for 3 days at 28 oC, the seed cultures were transferred to 1000 mL  Erlenmeyer flask containing 200 mL of the N4 medium in a ratio  of  5%  (v/v).  A  total  of  20  L  cultures  were  made  by  this  way.   Fermentations were performed on a rotary shaker (200 rpm) for 7  days  at  28  oC.    The  fermentation  broths  were  separated  to  supernatant and mycelia cakes by configuration at 4000 rmp for  10  min.  The  secondary  metabolites  in  the  supernatants  were  absorbed  by  XAD-7HP  resins,  which  were  eluted  with  8  L  acetone.  The  mycelia  cakes  were  extracted  4  times  with  4  L  methanol.  After  evaporation  of  organic  solvents  under  vacuum,  the residues were combined and re-extracted with 2 L butanone.  After  drying  under  vacuum,  crude  extracts  (25.0  g)  were  obtained.  The  crude  extracts  were  subjected  to  normal  phase  silica  gel  column  (100  -  200  mesh,  100  g),  and  eluted  with  CHCl3/CH3OH/H2O  (95/5/0.5, 90/10/1,  v/v,  each  of  600  mL)  to  yield  2  fractions  (Fr.1  to  Fr.2).  Fr.2  was  separated  by  an  ODS  column  (50  µm,  YMC*GEL  ODS-A-HG,  30  g)  on  a  Ag

2  fractions  (Fr.1  to  Fr.2).  Fr.2  was  separated  by  an  ODS  column  (50  µm,  YMC*GEL  ODS-A-HG,  30  g)  on  a  Agela  Cheetahtm  MP200  MPLC  workstation,  and  eluted  with  a  gradient  of  CH3OH/H2O  (10%-100%,  v/v)  for  1.5  h  to  obtain  4  sub-fractions  (Fr.2.1  to  Fr.2.5).  The  Fr.2.2  was  further  purified  by  semi-preparative  HPLC  (solvent  A,  0.1%  formic  acid  in  water;  solvent  B,  90%  CH3CN  in  water;  eluted  with  constant  55% solvent B; flow rate at 2.5 mL/min) to yield nenestatin A (1,  7.0 mg).

Fermentation  of  the  ∆nes27  mutant  (a  total of  20  L  cultures)  and  preparation  of  the  crude  extracts  (6.0  g)  were  performed  in  similar  ways  as  described  for  the  wild  type  strain.  The  crude  extracts were subjected to normal phase silica gel column (100 -  200 mesh, 40 g), and eluted with petroleum ether/CHCl3 (100/0,  3/1, 1/1, 0/100, v/v, each of 600 mL) to yield 4 fractions (Fr.1 to  Fr.4).  The Fr.4 was separated by Sephadex LH20 and was eluted  with CHCl3/ CH3OH (1:1, V/V) to obtain 4 sub-fractions (Fr.4.1  to  Fr.4.4).  The  Fr.4.3  was  further  purified  by  semi-preparative  HPLC  (solvent  A,  0.1%  formic  acid  in  water;  solvent  B,  90%  MeCN in water; eluted with constant 50% solvent B; flow rate at  2.5 mL/min) to yield homo-dehydrorabelomycin E (2, 42.0 mg).  4.6.
